{"cursor":"1658","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"'Sociological intelligence' is military or competitive intelligence concerning\nthe social stratification, value systems, and group dynamics of a population.\n\nSociological intelligence is useful to a military intelligence system because\nsociological concepts are key to understanding a region's stability, military\ncapability, and foreign policy. The importance of sociological\nintelligence has been demonstrated most prominently in recent conflicts in the\nformer Yugoslavia, Africa, Russia, and the Middle East. The United States'\nfailure to employ sociological intelligence assets was detrimental to dealing\nwith revolutionary Iran, when ignorance and stereotyping of Iranian leadership\nas \"radicals\" limited U.S. understanding of the situation. {{cite\nencyclopedia\n | year = 2009 title = Intelligence (military) - sociological encyclopedia =\n | EncyclopÃ¦dia Britannica publisher = EncyclopÃ¦dia Britannica location = id =\n}}\n\nIn competitive intelligence the term is used to describe a field of sociological\nenquiry into potential markets or business competitors. {{Cite book\n|title=Competitive intelligence and global business |page=62\n|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group |year=2005 |first=David L. |last=Blenkhorn\n|url=http://books.google.co.uk/books?id=qV3UEo0K0zcC |isbn=0-275-98140-\n1|accessdate=26 April 2009}}\n","linknr":85,"url":"Sociological_intelligence","recorded":1372155949,"links":["/w/index.php?title=Sociological_intelligence&action=edit","/w/index.php?title=Sociological_intelligence&action=edit","//bits.wikimedia.org/favicon/wikipedia.ico","/w/opensearch_desc.php","//en.wikipedia.org/w/api.php?action=rsd","//creativecommons.org/licenses/by-sa/3.0/","/w/index.php?title=Special:RecentChanges&feed=atom","//bits.wikimedia.org/en.wikipedia.org/load.php?debug=false&lang=en&modules=ext.gadget.DRN-wizard%2CReferenceTooltips%2Ccharinsert%2Cteahouse%7Cext.rtlcite%2Cwikihiero%7Cmediawiki.l